docs.lead_paragraph: With health-care costs soaring and an estimated 46 million Americans uninsured, many see cause for despair. Others see opportunity — for retail medical care. This year, a company called QuickHealth opened several clinics in Northern California — some in pharmacies, one inside a Wal-Mart — offering primary care on a pay-as-you-go, first-come-first-served basis seven days a week. For $39, a patient can have a 15-minute consultation with a licensed physician. A comprehensive physical is $59, while on-the-spot cholesterol tests, rapid strep tests and diabetes screenings are $29 each. For $99, the clinic offers wound suturing (including local anesthetic and a return visit to remove the stitches), while $199 buys the HealthyLover package, including physical exam and H.I.V. and S.T.D. tests.
